	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />My childhood trick for the NES was, after you push the cart down, use your two index fingers and kinda wiggle the cart out a little bit, and point the back end of the cart to the left. That usually solved most connection problems.
<br />
<br />My other trick was to just use a game genie without any codes. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" />
<br />
<br />As far as garbled graphics, my current front-loading NES has a problem where, if I don't use it for a long time, the graphics just <em>will not</em> work correctly (which also breaks SMB's title screen), and no amount of cleaning/fiddling will fix it. However, after playing some games like normal (despite the glitched graphics), the graphics will fix themselves, and the NES will work fine for months and months. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" />
<br />
<br />Maybe your NES does this too?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
